Public procurement of works and Prevention of corruption
Joint report by the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Court of audit of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits
Introduction and Overview
The award of services by contracting authorities is of great importance for both the state and the economy.
It is the responsibility of the state to use public funds as economically and sparingly as possible and to ensure fair and regulated competition.
In the European Union (EU), contracting authorities ' award of services is an important element in the creation of a single Economic Area.
In order to ensure largely unrestricted competition, including cross-border, contracting authorities must comply with EU rules on the award of contracts above certain value limits (thresholds).
To this end, the EU member states have to transfer and apply EU procurement law into national law.
This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.
Below the EU thresholds, it is up to the individual countries to regulate the award of public contracts themselves.
The procurement of services is also a corruption-prone area.
In view of the generally high potential for damage, contracting authorities are therefore required to take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and undue advantages in the award of their contracts.
In January 2011, the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the federal Accounting Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits on both the EU-wide award of construction services and the Prevention of corruption.
The focus of the audits was on the application of the EU procurement law, each implemented in national regulations, as well as the Prevention of corruption in the procurement of construction services in building construction and road construction or transport infrastructure.
The awards below the EU threshold were also included in the consideration with regard to the Prevention of corruption.
The audit results of both sais are summarised in this joint report.
The report should also be addressed to international bodies, such as the International Organisation of supreme audit institutions (INTOSAI).
Audit areas and audited entities the evaluations of the Federal Court of auditors on the listed topics are mainly based on cross - sectional audits carried out in 2011/2012 at the building authorities responsible for the road construction and building construction of the federal government in Germany.
In doing so, he examined, for example, the construction of highways and major building projects.
In addition, the Bundesrechnungshof drew on results from previous investigations.
The Supreme control Office of the Czech Republic submitted its evaluations, audit findings from the years 2008 to 2011. The examinations included construction work in road construction, railway infrastructure construction, water engineering, building construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) and other construction areas in the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the federal government's public procurement contracts are predominantly awarded by the building authorities of the federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the State Building administration is centrally responsible for the procurement of transport infrastructure.
In building construction, the awards are carried out decentrally by those bodies using state budgetary resources.
In both countries, freelancers are also involved in certain areas of procurement procedures.
When comparing the evaluations, differences in public procurement law and in the market structure for construction services in both countries must be taken into account.
Structure of the public procurement law in both countries
In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.
Procurement procedures limited to the national sphere are governed by budgetary law and the administrative provisions based on it.
In addition, for both EU-wide and national procurement, many additional individual rules are laid down by internal administrative provisions,
such as the so-called" procurement manuals " of the federal government, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or further formulated in accordance with the law on procurement law.
In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed exclusively by the Procurement Act and other statutory provisions, which apply to both the above and below the EU thresholds.
The procurement law was substantially amended in 2012.
The new regulation reinforced transparency in the management of public funds, enabled greater competition and limited the opportunities for corruption in procurement procedures.
Principles of Public Procurement Law in both countries
In both countries, the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiated procedure shall apply in particular to EU-wide awards.
In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold apply the National Procurement types (Public Procurement, restricted procurement, free-hand procurement), but which largely correspond to the above-mentioned EU-wide procurement types.
Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of the priority of the open procedure (in the case of EU-wide procurement) and the public procurement procedure (in the case of national procurement).
In the open procedure and in the public tender, any interested undertaking may submit a tender.
Another essential feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of small and medium-sized enterprises.
This is mainly due to the division of an overall construction measure into technical and partial lots.
The individual award of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.
Both of the above-mentioned features of German public procurement law are proven tools for achieving economic results.
More than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees are active in Germany.
In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures are also applicable for construction projects below the EU threshold.
An exception to this is the simplified procedure, where a less stringent procedure may be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.
Czech public procurement law provides, in accordance with EU law, for contracts to be concluded when competition is guaranteed and a favourable price is achieved.
The current legal provisions in the Czech Republic make it possible for contracting entities to choose between open and non-open procedures.
There are over 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 are companies with 20 or more employees.
