Summary of the results of the parallel audits
The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the federal Accounting Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) conducted parallel audits in their countries on the EU-wide award of construction services and the Prevention of corruption.
In this context, the working groups of both sais compared the relevant legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany, as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the areas of building construction and road construction.
In doing so, they found essentially:
The EU directives on the award of works by contracting authorities have been transposed into national law in both the Czech Republic and Germany (Nos. 1 and 3.1).
In addition to the EU requirements, the Prevention of corruption is also facilitated by the procurement rules of both countries, which partly differ in their priorities and their details (no 3.2).
In both countries, an essential requirement for the procurement documents is that they contain all the information necessary for the proper preparation of the tender.
The service descriptions must be neutral and must not contain any restrictions on competition.
In Germany, the procurement documents have largely met these requirements.
In the Czech Republic, it is still a Problem to determine the subject-matter sufficiently.
In Germany, construction works must be divided into lots as far as possible in order to promote competition.
Following the findings of the BRH, this requirement was largely implemented in Germany.
The NKÚ noted in its road construction audits in particular that the award of large-scale services without lots or with very large lots could affect competition and lead to a restriction to only a few large companies.
Narrowing the market potential can lead to significant cost increases and pose the risk of price or other agreements.
In accordance with the provisions of both countries, contracting entities may, under certain conditions, agree on additional or modified services which are necessary after the initial contract has been concluded (no 4.1).
The respective specifications for determining the type of award were largely followed in both countries.
According to the regulations of the Czech Republic, Contracting entities may choose between open and restricted procedures.
In Germany, on the other hand, the legal and budgetary priority of the open procedure applies to EU-wide contracts or the public invitation to tender, which corresponds to the open procedure for national contracts.
This allows more companies to make offers.
This reduces the risk of corruption, hinders price agreements between bidders and leads to the most economic results.
In the case of construction projects whose estimated total order values reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited construction authorities generally awarded construction services throughout Europe.
The correct estimate of the expected value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of contract.
In Germany, cost databases are used for the calculation of costs for public buildings, particularly in building construction,
this is based on the evaluations of completed construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, a database is used in the field of road construction, but it is not yet an effective tool (no 4.2).
In the case of works to be awarded throughout Europe, preliminary information and notices must be published. The aim is to strengthen competition by enabling interested companies to adapt to the planned contracts at an early stage.
As a rule, the audited building authorities complied with this requirement.
In some cases, incorrect information, incorrect applications or lack of controls may affect competition (no 4.3).
The selection of candidates for participation in public procurement procedures is particularly susceptible to manipulation.
Under EU law, the number of candidates invited shall be sufficient to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria shall be objective, shall not discriminate and shall be disclosed in advance.
In addition to EU requirements, contracting entities in both countries should move as often as possible between the companies to be called up for selection.
In order to counter the risk of manipulation, there are in some cases very detailed requirements in Germany.
In some cases, these requirements were not taken into account by the audited administrations.
In the Czech Republic, decisions on the selection of candidates were not always comprehensible (no 4.4).
In both countries, during the tendering phase, in order to ensure equal competition, the same information shall be provided to undertakings interested in submitting tenders.
In order to avoid anticompetitive agreements, it is necessary to avoid any contact between these companies and freelancers who have been involved in drawing up the specifications.
The corresponding regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.
The audited building authorities in Germany did not comply with these requirements in part (no 4.5).
In both countries, the principle of extra expenditure and the principle of transparency must be taken into account when opening the offers.
The requirements for the identification, documentation, safekeeping and confidentiality of the offers are intended to narrow the scope for manipulation and are particularly specified in Germany.
The tests in both countries revealed few objections (no 4.6).
Examination and evaluation of the offers are defined in both countries by guidelines for the structure and process organisation.
The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but have not been consistently observed by the audited contracting entities.
For example, contracting entities handed over offers to third parties for examination without prior examination of the offers and sufficient documentation of anomalies.
The offers were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (no 4.7).
When the EU-wide procurement procedures are concluded, the parties to the competition will be informed of the proposed procurement.
This possibility of legal protection also has a preventive function against corruption.
The Czech Republic also provides for judicial review of non-EU procurement procedures.
In only a few cases, the contracting entities did not comply with the time limits laid down in the procurement procedures or did not comply with the tenderers ' offer in terms of content (no 4.8).
The documentation of the procurement procedures was not always complete or comprehensible at the audited building administrations in both countries.
In this respect, the EU-wide requirement for transparency was not sufficiently implemented in the procurement notices of certain procedures.
Some of the shortcomings identified also reduced the anti-corruption function of the documentation.
The contracting authorities of both countries largely complied with their reporting and reporting obligations (no 4.9).
Principles of EU procurement law and the Prevention of corruption
EU procurement law
In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union with free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, inter alia, the procurement coordination directive and the remedies directive, which had to be transposed into national law by the member states.
The general procurement principles of the European Union are, in particular, the competitive bid, the equal treatment bid or the Prohibition of discrimination and the transparency bid.
In order to achieve these objectives, the procurement coordination directive contains specific rules for construction work to be performed at EU level in the case of construction projects.
For this purpose, their expected order amounts must reach or exceed a current amount of 5,000,000 euros.
The regulations concern, in particular, documents the content of the Award, the publication of certain information before, during, and after the award, to Comply with deadlines, including for the receipt of tenders, the documentation of the procurement procedure, the requirements that can be placed on the qualifications of the applicants and The remedies Directive provides the basis for the legal protection of candidates and tenderers.
In the event of possible infringements of the public procurement law, the undertakings concerned may have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in review proceedings.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the European Union directives in national law.
The prevention of corruption
Importance of preventing corruption
In both countries there is no legal Definition of the concept of corruption.
In general, corruption is the abuse of a trust to a private advantage,
the i. d. R. will be initiated by the beneficiaries of these decisions.
Corruption can hinder competition and cause significant economic damage.
It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of world economic output.
For the European Union, the amount of these costs is estimated at 1%.
In the case of contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair practices may call into question confidence in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of contracting authorities.
In doing so, they have to review the organisation of their administrative structures and procedures for areas at risk of corruption in order to take appropriate safeguards against corruption.
Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the susceptibility of decision-making processes to corrupt abuse.
The award of public works is generally regarded as a particularly corruption-prone area of work.
Measures to prevent corruption
In Germany, corruption – in particular bribery and bribery, as well as acceptance and authorisation of benefits-is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
In order to prevent corruption, the federal government has adopted a directive and recommendations on corruption prevention in the federal administration. In addition to risk analysis, the following principles must be observed: priority of public tenders and open procedures, multi - eye principle and transparency, fundamental separation of Planning, Award and billing, accurate and complete documentation of procurement procedures.
In addition, further anti-corruption provisions have been incorporated into public procurement legislation.
For example, the Federal Ministry responsible for public procurement in the federal highways introduced an electronically supported control system in 2011,
with the procurement data − such as the estimated costs and the order amounts-as well as information about the persons involved in the professional activity are collected and evaluated for anomalies.
In the Czech Republic, corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
The legal requirements for transparency and equal treatment of tenderers, as well as the Prohibition of any discrimination, constitute the most important basis for preventing corruption.
For public procurement, the Czech government has adopted anti-corruption measures in a strategy paper on combating corruption for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated for the years 2013 to 2014.
Some of the measures recommended in this directive have already been transposed into National Public Procurement Law and related administrative provisions by 14.
The main provisions of the new legislation are: reduction of the thresholds for smaller contracts; obligation to prior publicise the award of contracts by the contracting entity, including indication of the grounds for tendering; Prohibition of the restriction of the number of tenderers in restricted procedures, thereby abolishing the possibility of selecting tenderers through lot procedures; introduction of the obligation to publish the procurement documents and all annexes; introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.
Examination results for each phase of the procurement procedure
Procurement documents
Procurement documents the procurement documents must contain all the information the tenderers need to produce an appropriate tender.
In particular, the procurement documents must allow a suitable calculation.
In doing so, tenderers must not be exposed to risks that cannot be calculated for them.
The procurement documents consist in particular of the specifications and the terms of the contract.
In addition, they contain the requirements for proof of the tenderers ' qualification (suitability) and the criteria which determine the selection of the most cost-effective offer.
Requirements of EU law and the Prevention of corruption
The requirements of EU law for the procurement documents are directed in particular to the technical specifications.
These must be equally accessible to all tenderers and should limit competition as little as possible.
The specifications must always be product-neutral.
For this reason, information on products or manufacturers as part of the specifications is only permitted under strict conditions.
Avoiding competitive constraints in procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of preventing corruption.
In addition, unclear or incorrect information in the procurement documents must be avoided, as they provide scope for speculations in the preparation of the offers and for manipulations in their evaluation.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar rules in both countries, the EU legal requirements for the technical specifications are transposed into national law.
In principle, the services are to be written off in a product-neutral manner without factory specifications.
In the service descriptions, the individual services must normally be subdivided into service units with respective quantity specifications in detail.
Prices must be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g. Euro per m2 or per unit).
Only in exceptional cases can Services be defined by functional targets.
In any case, the specifications must be complete and unambiguous.
They shall contain precise quantities and shall not include services for which it is not determined whether they are needed.
Remuneration according to flat rates or according to time expenditure shall be avoided as far as possible.
The purpose of these provisions is to prevent speculation and manipulation based on undetermined specifications in the procurement documents.
The service descriptions must enable tenderers to produce their services safely and without extensive preparatory work.
The invitation to tender shall not be made public until the procurement documents have been completed.
Different rules
There is no obligation to tender works in lots in the Czech Republic.
If it is possible by the nature of the service to be performed, the public contracting authorities may subdivide the works into several lots.
In Germany, construction works are generally to be divided into lots, separated by the quantity (partial lots) and / or by type or subject area (specialised lots).
The aim is to enable small and medium-sized enterprises to participate in the competition, to expand the number of possible suppliers and to make price agreements more difficult.
This type of award is considered to be the most economical as a rule.
Evaluation criteria must be specified in the procurement documents in the Czech Republic both in the EU-wide and in the national procedures.
The aim is to ensure that applicants are fully and finally able to identify the criteria according to which their offers are to be evaluated.
In Germany, the indication of evaluation criteria is required in EU-wide notices, but at the latest in the procurement documents, only in EU-wide procurement procedures.
In the case of national award procedures, the evaluation criteria shall only be recorded in an internal administrative award notice.
In Germany, procurement documents drawn up by authorised freelancers may not contain any references to these offices or involved planners or reviewers in the building construction and some road construction administrations.
The aim is to prevent individual companies from obtaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages through contact with these freelancers without the knowledge of the customer.
This is also the reason why freelance procurement documents are not allowed to send or interpret planning documents for inspection.
The contact person of the company is the customer alone.
There is currently no provision in the Czech Republic for this.
Additional or modified services, which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (supplements), are almost always incurred for large construction projects.
In both countries, the legal provisions allow, to a certain extent, the awarding of supplements to the company that has already been appointed, without the need for a public procurement procedure.
According to the EU regulations and the German regulations, the remuneration of supplementary services may not exceed half of the main contract.
In addition, the additional services must not be separated from the main order without major disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.
In the Czech Republic, a narrower limit of 20% applies to such contracts without public notice.
However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need for an additional contractor to participate in the already ongoing construction work.
If supplementary services are also transferred to the company that has already been commissioned, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is in principle not possible according to the regulations in Germany.
In determining the remuneration for the additional services, the agreed prices and the basis for determining the price of the order already placed are to be assumed.
In addition to supplementary benefits, there may also be a reduction in the scope of benefits.
In the Czech Republic, lower volumes cannot be offset against additional supplementary services.
Key Audit Findings
BHR
Technical specifications and product-neutral invitation to tender
In some cases, the specifications included references to national technical approvals or standards that had already been replaced by Europe-wide standards.
Some service descriptions also included product-related specifications – for example, graffiti protection, joint tapes or noise protection plates-without this being necessary.
In some cases, performance requirements were described in such detail that only one product was considered.
Subdivided by services
The BRH has not found in any of the proceedings examined violations of the command to write out services in a list of services broken down by partial services.
Completeness of service descriptions
In the vast majority of cases, the procurement documents were completed before the start of the tendering procedures.
In some cases, the procurement documents had to be corrected during the tender phase, as some items or deadlines had changed.
In some cases, the service directories contained items where it was not clear whether they were needed.
A service schedule for demolition work even consisted almost half of such demand items.
Lots and evaluation criteria
In the case of many awards, there was no prescribed justification for the fact that the services, which were mainly offered by non-specialists, were not further divided into non-specialists.
There were no objections when specifying the criteria to be used for the evaluation of tenders.
References to freelancers
A small part of the service descriptions contained references to the persons involved in freelance work.
Their names were partly on the cover sheets or in attached plans or expert opinions.
In one case, the contracting authority even explicitly asked the applicants to contact the architect "on questions of tendering".
In the building sector in particular, the contracting authorities mainly attributed the objections raised to failures of the freelancers responsible for drawing up the service descriptions.
The Construction Services pointed to the lack of capacity in order to be able to adequately monitor the specifications.
NKÚ
Technical specifications and product-neutral tendering In public procurement for the construction of a residential building with 12 residential units were specified in the performance description a supplier as well as a particular brand of product.
The contracting entity did not allow the use of comparable products without justification.
During the construction of several higher education buildings, suppliers and products were also specified in the invitation to tender.
Performance descriptions with performance units
In the case of construction projects in some industrial areas, the contracting entity did not clearly specify the scope and nature of the required services in the specifications.
As a power unit, it merely indicated the space of the individual buildings in cubic meters.
Completeness of service descriptions
In the construction of a motorway bypass, the specifications were modified four times during the period August to September 2009 as part of a non-open procedure,
as the volume of services increased considerably and the technical requirements had changed.
Tender documents for Social buildings included inaccurate location information, insufficient preliminary structural studies and incomplete design drawings, which required additional services.
When building a large library building, the specifications of the Interior did not contain any requirements for product quality.
As a result of these lack of specifications, some subcontractors installed overpriced and inappropriate high-quality equipment.
Lots and selection criteria
In the Czech Republic, the division of construction work into partial lots or the award of partial lots is not compulsory.
An examination of the three large sections of the construction of a motorway ring showed that if selected parts were allocated in lots, savings of up to € 31.6 million would have been possible with a total cost of € 620.3 million.
For example, six different buildings which were the subject of a single contract alone would have saved EUR 2.5 million (25 %) if they were awarded in lots.
If the construction of 20 bridges were to be allocated separately, savings of EUR 11.5 million (25 %) would have been possible compared to a total allocation.
In the award of construction services in road construction, the central contracting authority set very extensive reference requirements as the selection criteria.
In the construction of a part of a motorway, the contracting entity requested the tenderers, in an open procedure, to prove, among other things, at least three road construction projects carried out, each worth EUR 28 million from the last five years.
In the Czech Republic, a maximum of nine providers met these requirements.
The public procurement of another part of a motorway included six separate construction projects for which the contracting entity had set an annual construction volume of at least EUR 480 million for the last three years as the criterion for the selection of the undertakings.
Two-thirds of the appropriations allocated to road construction projects in 2008 and 2009 (i.e. EUR 2.5 billion out of a total of EUR 3.7 billion) were allocated to contracts awarded by a total of five companies that carried out the contracts alone or as a working group.
For 46 procurement procedures with an order volume of 528 million euros, only two or even one bidder made an offer.
The NKÚ showed that narrowing the market potential could lead to significant cost increases.
Additional Services
In the case of the construction of a motorway bypass, the contracting authority did not apply any of the legal procedures in two cases when additional services were awarded, nor did it conclude any written contracts for the additional services.
Due to unclear quantity and quality requirements, additional revenues were generated in the first case of up to EUR 63.7 million (net) and in the second case up to EUR 165.4 million (net), resulting in an increase in the respective order volume of 21% and 91% respectively.
