This comparison indicates that motorway construction in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in Germany.
Summary Findings
The basic rules on procurement documents are broadly consistent in both countries and take into account EU requirements.
They serve both comprehensive and fair competition and prevent corruption.
For example, the requirement for sufficient determination of the service descriptions is intended to enable tenderers to properly calculate and produce their offers,
protect the customer from additional services to be agreed at a later date and also contain scope for speculation.
In Germany, the common basic requirements for procurement documents are supplemented by regulations aimed at further reducing restrictions on competition and manipulation possibilities.
In the Czech Republic, there are no requirements to this extent, but transparency is enhanced by the publication of the evaluation criteria for non-EU award procedures.
The specifications have been met to a large extent in both countries.
In some cases, however, deviations had to be objected, which could also have led to restrictions of competition.
In Germany, the existing bid for the formation of Lots promotes competition and leads to economic outcomes.
In the Czech Republic, according to the examination findings of the NKÚ, the awarding of large services without lots or with only very large lots of restrictions on the supplier field can result in only a few large companies.
The extensive reference requirements laid down in the Czech Republic in road construction have meant that public contracts are awarded only to a narrow circle of suppliers and that small and medium-sized enterprises are not allowed to participate in the competition.
Also, a limited number of competitors often leads to higher prices and increases the risk of price or other agreements.
In the case of the award and remuneration of additional or modified services, the regulatory approaches differ in both countries.
According to the EU regulations and the German regulations, supplementary services with a value up to half of the main contract can be awarded without public procurement under certain conditions.
In the Czech Republic, a narrower limit of 20% applies, up to which additional services can be awarded without notice to the original contractor in the negotiated procedure.
