Specify the type of award and take into account the EU threshold
By defining the type of award, the contracting authority determines the size of the number of companies participating in the competition.
It may leave the range of potential candidates and tenderers largely Unlimited, for example by selecting an open procedure, or by specifying non-public procurement procedures.
In the case of construction projects where a threshold set by the EU is reached or exceeded, European-wide procurement procedures shall be applied.
Requirements of EU law and the Prevention of corruption
When selecting the type of award, the contracting authority shall take into account, in particular, the competition and transparency requirements of European law.
If the estimated total contract value of the works of a project is at or above the EU threshold of currently 5,000,000 euros, the works are generally to be awarded in Europe by open or non-open procedures.
In exceptional cases, negotiated procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
The contracting authority may, in the case of works which reach or exceed the EU threshold, derogate to a limited extent from the principle of pan-European Procurement and award works in national procurement procedures, provided that the estimated contract value of each lot is less than EUR 1,000,000 and the sum of these lots does not exceed 20% of the
A single construction project must not be divided into individual measures without compelling reasons or deliberately estimated at low cost values in order to avoid the obligation to generally award construction services across Europe.
As competition restrictions significantly increase the risk of manipulation, the choice of the award type becomes very important in preventing corruption.
The detailed justification of the type of award chosen and the examination of the obligation to apply EU procurement rules are important components of the documentation of the procurement procedure.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
Both countries have fully transposed EU procurement and threshold requirements into national law.
Different rules
The Czech Republic has also transferred the principle of equal treatment of open and non-open procedures contained in the EU directive to its construction contracts which are not subject to EU requirements.
There is freedom of choice between the open and the non - open procedure, without the decision having to be documented or substantiated. However, other procedures are only possible under certain legally defined conditions.
In Germany, on the other hand, the open procedure or, in the case of national awards, the public invitation to tender generally takes precedence. This is laid down by budgetary and public procurement law as well as by the anti - corruption guidelines.
Other types of procurement – such as the restricted procedure or restricted tendering − are only possible in exceptional cases, which are finally regulated in the procurement law.
The existence of an exception must be clearly justified and documented.
The principle of the priority of the open procedure or the public invitation to tender is intended to ensure as unlimited competition as possible, to exclude the possibility of manipulation by setting it on specific tenderers and to make possible price agreements between tenderers more difficult.
The principle of public procurement is a central Element in preventing corruption in Germany.
The correct estimate of the expected value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of contract.
The construction services in Germany can use planning and cost databases of public administrations as well as other organisations to determine the expected costs in the field of Public Building Construction.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects. The databases contain, among other things, cost indicators for building categories, usage units, components or individual construction services.
On the basis of such cost parameters, the expected order value of a planned forecast or a construction work to be awarded can be determined.
Corresponding cost databases for road construction have in Germany only some construction administrations.
However, a nationwide introduction is planned for all road authorities.
Contracting entities in the Czech Republic are not able to use central databases or average price calculations of comparable construction measures to determine the expected cost of construction work.
In most cases, cost calculations are based on estimates made by the financing body or on the amount of funds made available to the building service.
Measures to standardize cost determination procedures are still in the early stages.
Within the framework of the Anti - Corruption Plan for 2011-2012, the relevant ministries were commissioned to create a database for standardised building materials and materials.
