Key audit findings BRH
Selection of the award procedure
The contracting entities audited largely wrote out the works in open procedures or in public procurement procedures, thus following the budgetary and public procurement rules.
In 2011, 59.5% of the federal construction services in building construction were put out to public or open tender.
In road construction, this share was 94.8%.
In the choice of non-public procurement types, detailed reasons were partly missing, why the contracting entities had to deviate from the principle of open procedure or public invitation to tender.
In a cross-cutting investigation, the BRH concluded, on the basis of more than 16,000 procurement procedures, that the non - public procurement types have significant competitive disadvantages compared to the open procedures and public procurement procedures and increase the risk of manipulation and corruption.
In the building sector, more than twice as many bids were submitted for Public Procurement As for restricted tenders and almost three times as many bids as for free-hand contracts.
The investigation also showed that, on average, bid prices were 6% and 10% higher for restricted tenders and open-ended tenders than for public tenders.
Parallel investigations by the Federal Ministry of construction and a state court of audit confirmed the economic differences between public and non-public procurement types.
The Federal Ministry of construction, as a result of its studies on economic efficiency, even found twice as high differences between public and non-public procurement procedures.
Taking into account the EU threshold
In the case of construction projects for which they had identified an estimated total contract amount of more than 5,000,000 Euro, the contracting entities audited generally drew up procurement plans in which they determined the works to be awarded by EU-wide as well as by national procurement procedures.
According to the public procurement plans, this has meant that more than 80% of the EU-wide construction work has always been allocated.
It was not possible to circumvent the obligation to award EU-wide contracts by means of too low cost estimates.
However, in part as a result of incorrect calculations, there was a de facto fall below the minimum share of EU-wide procurement procedures.
During the construction phase, some contracting entities improperly changed the specifications of their procurement plans.
They did not substantiate these changes and did not demonstrate that the minimum share of EU-wide procurement procedures was still being complied with.
For most of the construction measures under review, the proportion of EU subcontracting according to the accounting results was usually lower than that foreseen under the procurement plan.
In some cases, contracting entities in the case of construction projects above the EU threshold do not comply with the requirement to write out all single lots of EUR 1,000,000 and more in EU-wide procedures,
and instead chose national procedures.
