Choice of the award procedure
In the case of several major construction projects, such as the construction of some motorway sections, construction projects in the context of a major sporting event and housing construction projects, the contracting sites divided construction work into several sub-orders, although these services were similar or comparable.
As a result of these splits, the individual benefits were no longer above the threshold and were then awarded in simplified procedures or even in disregard of legal requirements.
Calculation methods for the estimated value of the contract
In road construction, existing price databases for this sector were insufficient to determine the expected value of the contract.
The data was based on recently completed construction projects, but there were indications of a lack of economic efficiency, unnecessary additional services or excessive profits of the commissioned companies.
For three sections of a motorway ring, actual prices were about 37% lower than the expected order values established by the database.
In the meantime, the Ministry of transport revised the databases in order to be able to take into account not only the supply prices of recent years but also comparable market prices and price increase indices in the construction sector.
In building construction, the expected order values were based on cost values estimated by the project architects or on investor estimates.
The actual order values differed greatly from the estimates.
The estimated price for the conversion or expansion of a large library was twice the value of the contract agreed at a later stage, but eight additions resulting from the construction work resulted in a cost increase of EUR 2.1 million and 27% respectively.
Similarly, the actual value of the contract for the construction of a library depot was 33% lower than the estimated price, with cost increases during the construction phase.
In other cases, supply prices exceeded estimates and increased during construction.
When building a large library, the estimated price was exceeded by 16 million euros or 22%. In the case of the construction of a judicial building, the costs rose disproportionately at 139%, as the usable area had only expanded by 12%.
