Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
The EU legal requirements for prior information and Publicity have been fully transposed into national law by both countries.
Different rules
In the Czech Republic, prior information and notices must also be published in the case of works not to be awarded throughout Europe.
Procurement procedures may be started at the earliest one month after dispatch of the prior information notice to the EU official journal (for EU-wide awards) or to the National Official Journal (for all awards).
Only in exceptional cases can the publication of a prior information notice be waived.
In Germany, no pre-information is required for non-EU procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, notices for public procurement and participation competitions must be published on the federal internet portal and, where applicable, also in newspapers or periodicals, prior to restricted tendering.
In the case of restricted calls for tenders without competition, notices of services to be awarded starting at 25,000 euros are required (Ex ante transparency).
The preliminary information shall include all planned lots of the construction projects.
In Germany,this is of particular importance because of the small proportion of loose construction contracts.
In the Czech Republic, this rule has only a small effect, since there much less construction work is divided into lots.
