Selection of candidates for non-public procurement
In contrast to public procurement procedures, non-public procurement procedures do not allow any undertaking interested in the performance of the services to be awarded to participate in the competition.
In the case of non-public procurement procedures, the contracting entity shall select in advance which undertakings are to be invited to submit tenders.
Requirements of EU Law and of corruption prevention EU regulations do not allow a limitation on the number of Applicants in the EU-wide public procurement procedure.
However, in the case of restricted procedures, at least five undertakings shall be invited to submit tenders.
For negotiated procedures with a contract notice, at least three undertakings shall be invited.
In any case, the number of candidates invited shall be sufficient to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not lead to discrimination and must be disclosed in advance.
The selection of companies to be called upon is a process within the procurement procedure that is highly susceptible to manipulation, for example by allowing certain companies to be preferred unilaterally.
In addition, restricting competition to a few companies also favours possible agreements between applicants.
In both cases, the distribution result may be significantly affected at the expense of the customer.
The contracting entities shall therefore take special measures to prevent possible manipulation, to carry out adequate controls and, in particular, to ensure the transparency and traceability of this procedural step.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
The arrangements for the selection of candidates are similar in both countries.
In addition to EU requirements, contracting entities should switch among the companies to be called upon as often as possible in the selection of candidates.
Nor should Competition be restricted to companies established in certain regions.
The contracting entities shall justify the selection of candidates and document the course of the selection procedure in their award notices.
Different rules
In Germany, at least three candidates must be invited to submit tenders in the case of restricted calls for tenders and, in the case of free-hand tenders, in principle, several suitable candidates must be invited to submit tenders.
Under the new Czech rules, it is inadmissible − with the exception of two special areas-to limit the number of tenderers in the case of restricted procedures and negotiated procedures.
In Germany, the multi-eye principle must be observed when selecting companies.
For example, a staff member has proposed a number of companies for a public procurement procedure, the management level of construction services or an agent of the awarding authority of this proposal in the rule change by taking out about a proposed business and/ or a new business Supplement.
The aim is to prevent a single Person from finally determining the group of companies to be involved in the competition.
Otherwise, in the case of manipulative intentions, this could enable far-reaching agreements to be reached between the parties.
The list of companies to be called upon must be kept confidential and not made available to the general public, even in respect of freelancers.
