Key Audit Findings
BRH
Number of applicants
The requirement to require a minimum number of undertakings to submit tenders in the case of non-public procurement was met, with a few exceptions.
An evaluation of the BRH of almost 7,000 non-Europe-wide procurement procedures of construction services in building construction revealed that the contracting authorities requested an average of 6.6 companies to submit bids for limited federal tenders in Germany and an average of 4.4 companies to submit bids for free tender.
Change of companies and regional restrictions
In particular, in the case of trades with a few suppliers, the contracting entities did not always change the range of candidates selected.
In particular, they took into account companies already known and tried and tested from their point of view.
As a result, they stated that, in the case of non-public proceedings, they had to ensure the suitability of the undertakings to be called upon to compete prior to the invitation to tender.
The BRH did not identify an inadmissible restriction to regional tenderers in the case of non-public procurement procedures, but it did identify a higher proportion of regional-based undertakings than in the case of public procurement procedures.
This was mainly due to the fact that the scope of services for non-public procurement procedures was on average much lower and therefore, for example, longer access routes were more important than for public procurement procedures.
More-eyes-principle and proposals freelance
Contrary to the rules, contracting entities mainly failed to have the proposed list of entities to be called upon modified by an independent Person.
In particular, they justified this with lack of processing capacity, time pressure or insufficient knowledge of alternative suitable companies.
In many cases, it was not documented who had proposed the companies invited to submit the tender.
Some samples showed that freelancers had drawn up the candidate lists and that these proposals had been accepted unchanged by the contracting entities.
Thus, the contracting entities did not protect themselves to the extent required from possible manipulations.
Confidentiality of bidders ' lists
At a contracting entity, the lists of companies to be called up were recorded in a data processing system that could be viewed by all staff members of that entity.
In the event of manipulative intentions, the names of the proposed or approved companies could have been passed on without authorisation and, for example, could have enabled agreements to be made between these companies.
Documentation
