Summary Findings
Because of the high danger of Manipulation in the selection of candidates in public procurement procedures, both countries have taken special measures to prevent undue restrictions of competition.
With the multi-eye principle, the secrecy of the bidders ' lists and the exclusive power of the contracting authorities to propose the companies to be called upon, the German provisions restrict such opportunities for abuse.
In the case of the Czech regulations, the newly introduced specification of the largely unlimited number of bidders for non-public proceedings can counteract possible manipulative restrictions.
However, the audit findings have shown that some of these requirements have been insufficiently implemented and that the potential for tampering with the field of participants has not been sufficiently reduced in these cases.
Contracting authorities should eliminate all the deficiencies identified.
Offer phase
The contract award notice or the invitation to tender shall commence at the stage of the tendering process in which undertakings may draw up tenders on the basis of the procurement documents sent to them.
Candidates may submit their tenders until the deadline set by the contracting entity.
Requirements of EU law and the Prevention of corruption
There are no separate EU legal requirements for this phase of the procurement procedure.
Contracting entities shall comply with the national rules designed to counteract the possibilities of manipulation existing during the offer phase.
These are mainly organizational requirements and controls.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
The procurement documents on the basis of which the undertakings are to draw up their offers shall, in principle, only be sent by the contracting entity.
Freelancers involved in the award procedure shall not carry out this task.
The contracting entity shall ensure that all candidates receive the same information during the tendering phase.
In the event of ambiguity in the procurement documents or other questions concerning the tendering procedure, only the contracting entity may provide information to the candidates.
Freelancers engaged in the preparation of the procurement documents may not provide any information.
During the entire offer period, contact between the appointed freelancers and the candidates must be prevented.
The freelancers must not become a hub of the procurement procedure through which contacts can be established with anticompetitive effects.
Tenders sent by Post or directly must be submitted in a sealed envelope.
Offers sent electronically shall be subject to technical encryption.
Different rules
In Germany, the contracting authority may also order external service providers to print and send the procurement documents, whose employees are obliged to maintain the confidentiality of the offers and to fulfil the contractual obligations conscientiously.
In Germany, the offers received must be marked with an entry stamp and sent directly, without delay and unopened to a member of staff responsible for safekeeping.
This staff member shall not be involved in the award.
The offers received must be closed by the opening date.
In the Czech Republic, the tenders received are marked with a reference number.
The contracting entity shall keep the offer data, including order numbers, as well as the creation and receipt data in a protocol.
The storage of offers is not specified in detail in the Czech Republic.
