Opening of tenders
Opening of tenders
During the opening date of the previously-sealed tenders will be opened and their contents read out, and thus made known.
From the opening date, tenderers shall be bound by their tenders until the end of the time limit set by the contracting entity.
Requirements of EU law and the Prevention of corruption
There are no separate EU legal rules for the opening up of offers.
However, the national anti-corruption rules contain extensive provisions for the protection of offers and competition during this highly sensitive Phase of the procurement procedure.
The multi-eye principle as well as the transparency and traceability of the Offer Opening are intended to prevent manipulation and changes to the submitted offers.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
The opening date shall be carried out by several persons to be designated by the contracting authority.
The multi-eye principle is intended to prevent individuals from uncontrolled manipulation of the offers when opening the offers.
In most procurement procedures, tenderers may participate in the opening date.
Only tenders submitted to the negotiator when the first tender was opened are eligible for opening.
Offers received late May no longer be considered.
The transparency of the opening date, the actions taken and the results of the offer opening in a log, including the names of the tenderers and the tender prices shall be recorded.
The protocol shall be read out and signed by the negotiating committee.
It can also be signed by the bidders present.
Different rules
In the Czech Republic, a committee shall open tenders.
It can also involve freelancers.
The committee may also be entrusted with further stages of the procurement procedure, such as the evaluation of tenders.
In Germany, a head of negotiation and a secretary shall open the tender.
The head of the negotiation shall be an official of the issuing body.
The head of the negotiation and, in the case of contracts in building construction, the Secretary shall not be involved in the processing of the contract documents or in the award and contract execution.
According to the German regulations, in addition to the offer prices, information on discounts and discounts as well as special features − such as damaged or delayed offers − must be recorded in the minutes of the opening date.
In the Czech Republic, in addition to the offer price, only the language of the offer and the applicant's right to sign are recorded.
The German regulations provide that the open offers must be marked in all parts in such a way that subsequent changes and additions are prevented.
The offers are generally characterized by perforations with the date of the opening date. They shall be kept secret after the opening date and may only be made available to persons directly responsible for the processing.
There are no corresponding Czech regulations.
If only one tender is received in a procurement procedure in the Czech Republic, this must not be opened and must be returned unvalued.
There is no such regulation in Germany. If only one offer is entered here, it must be opened and then valued.
