Summary Findings
The rules of both countries for the opening-up of tenders are in substantial parts identical. They take into account both the additional expenditure principle and the transparency principle. As a result, the risks of corruption and manipulation in the opening of offers can be substantially limited.
The requirements in Germany are more comprehensive than those in the Czech Republic.
In particular, the requirements for precise documentation of the procedure as well as for labelling, safe storage and confidentiality of offers significantly restrict manipulation options such as subsequent changes to offers.
In addition, the persons responsible for the opening of the offers shall not carry out any other tasks in connection with the service to be rendered.
All in all, only a few complaints prove the high acceptance of the specifications for the opening of the offer.
Examination and evaluation of tenders
Examination and evaluation of offers the client shall examine and evaluate the offers available at the opening date.
It shall determine the offer for the award of the contract which best meets the requirements according to the given award criteria.
Requirements of EU law and the Prevention of corruption
The EU's guidelines provide for a multi-level procedure:
First, the suitability of the tenderers must be determined.
Tenderers must be economically and financially viable and possess the necessary professional and technical expertise.
In principle, companies that have been convicted of bribery or fraud, for example, must be excluded from participating in the procurement procedure.
The tenders of the non-excluded tenderers shall be examined in terms of calculation, technical and economic terms and shall be assessed on the basis of the award criteria previously announced.
The client shall determine the most economically advantageous tender. Tenders with abnormally low prices must be examined by the client in particular.
The examination and evaluation of the tenders is a phase of the award procedure that is particularly susceptible to manipulation.
For example, tenderers may be excluded unjustifiably or tenders which do not meet the requirements may be left in competition.
By favouring or discriminating bidders, the score can be unduly affected and thus the finding of the most economically advantageous offer can be prevented.
The contracting entity shall therefore take special measures to ensure that the persons responsible for verification and evaluation fulfil the requirements for integrity and expertise.
It shall also ensure the transparency and traceability of the procedure and the decisions taken.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
In line with the requirements of the EU, offers in both countries must be examined and evaluated in multi-level procedures.
The requirements relating to the suitability of undertakings to be submitted, the award criteria to be taken into account in the evaluation and their weighting are laid down in the notices or in the procurement documents and cannot be modified during the procedure.
Once the suitability of the tender has been verified, the selection criteria may no longer be used in the evaluation of the tenders.
The evaluation shall be limited to the award criteria.
The submitted offers must first be examined formally as soon as possible to determine whether they are complete and whether they contain, for example, anomalies that could indicate potential manipulation intentions.
If tenderers are excluded from further examination and evaluation of their offers, they shall be informed thereof immediately.
If the evaluation of the tenders results in an abnormally low price, the tenderer must be given the opportunity to comment before a possible exclusion of his tender.
The decisions taken during the examination and evaluation of the offers must be documented in a comprehensible manner.
Different rules
In Germany, the offers to be kept secret may only be made available to persons directly responsible for the processing.
The examination of the offers and the calculation of the offers may only be carried out by the contracting authority.
It shall enter only staff who are not concerned with the award decision or the implementation of the measure.
The performance of the other audit and evaluation tasks is not regulated in detail.
If freelancers are entrusted with the examination and evaluation, they must treat the offers confidentially.
They may only make proposals for the decisions to be taken by the contracting entities.
In the Czech Republic, contracting committees shall be set up for the purpose of examining and evaluating tenders.
The committees draw up evaluation reports with award proposals.
In the end, as in Germany, only the contracting authorities have to decide on the award of contracts.
If the documents or declarations required for submission of tenders in Germany are only partially submitted, the contracting entity shall give the tenderers the opportunity to submit the missing documents within six days.
Only if the documents are still not available after the deadline, the offer is excluded from the evaluation.
In the Czech Republic, it is at the discretion of the contracting entity whether it gives tenderers the opportunity to complete missing evidence or declarations.
If a bidder fails to do so, it must be excluded.
In Germany, in addition to the total price, the standard prices (prices for partial services) of the offers must be examined.
If, due to the price structure of the offer, there is evidence of prices being set too low or too high for partial services, the Bidder shall be asked to clear up these ambiguities.
If he fails to do so and the contracting entity can provide proof of a mixed calculation of the prices, this offer shall be excluded.
The aim is to prevent bidders from speculating on significant changes in the volume of partial services when calculating their offer, which can lead to significant cost increases in the construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, the total price is assessed, but not the appropriateness of the prices for partial services.
A mixed calculation cannot justify the exclusion of an offer.
No contract may be awarded in Germany for offers with excessively high or low prices.
If one or more offers fall short of the applicable price determination of the customer or the offer totals of the other tenderers by 10% or more, the tenderers must prove the correct calculation of their offers.
If you are unable to do so, the contracting entity may exclude the offers concerned.
In the Czech Republic, the invitation to tender may be cancelled after verification of economic viability if only tenders with unjustifiable low prices are available.
In contrast to German public procurement law, the contract cannot be denied for this reason for offers with prices substantially higher than the customer's calculation.
If there is a suspicion of restrictive behaviour in Germany, the contracting authority must immediately report to its level of specialist supervision.
The latter shall decide on the measures to be taken and whether the Antitrust Authority or the public prosecutor's office should be informed.
The expert Supervisory level must agree to, for example, also for works over 50,000 Euro, if private contracts, a surcharge not to the tender with the lowest price, or by tender shall be cancelled.
There are no regulations in the Czech Republic.
Key Audit Findings
BRH
Suitability and evaluation criteria
The vast majority of the procurement procedures examined complied with the requirements set out above.
In the case of some proposed firms, the contracting entities did not themselves verify the suitability of the firms.
A recipient of the grant contracted companies without the required proof of suitability being available in full.
In some cases, it was not clear whether the contracting entity would take into account all the award criteria disclosed in its selection decision or whether it had merely used the 'price' criterion for its award decision.
Selection of the persons involved and confidentiality of offers
Some contracting entities used unapproved persons when examining the tenders.
For example, freelancers or staff members of the service responsible for planning or carrying out a construction project carried out tasks which were to be carried out only by staff of the contracting authority.
The construction services justified this with insufficient personnel capacity in the respective areas.
In some cases, employees who were not obliged to maintain the confidentiality of the offers and to fulfil the contractual obligations conscientiously were also involved in the freelance work involved in the examination of the offers.
For the construction services, it was usually not clear whether the offers were available to the freelancers only to the persons directly responsible for the processing.
Review and calculation of offers
Some contracting entities handed over the open offers to freelancers for further examination, without having previously carried out the prescribed review of the offers and the computational examination itself and their results documented.
In the case of manipulative intentions, third parties could have made changes to the offers without this being comprehensible to the contracting entities.
