If a tenderer submits a request for review within the Information period, the conclusion of a contract is only possible after the final decision in the review procedure.
Companies may also have the award decision reviewed by an independent court as part of this review process.
The review procedure shall ensure the legal protection of the undertakings and shall encourage the contracting entity to comply with the procurement law throughout the procurement procedure.
For this purpose, the procedure must be documented sufficiently.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
Both countries have implemented EU rules on information and verification procedures.
In both countries, the contracting entity shall decide on the award of the contract.
However, it must not deviate arbitrarily from the result of a proper examination and evaluation of the offers.
The contracting authority shall issue the order within the specified time limit,
also because the tenderers are no longer bound by their offers after the deadline.
In the case of open and restricted procedures or public and restricted tenders, the contracting entity may not deviate from the content of the tender when concluding the contract.
The unsuccessful tenderers shall be informed in a timely manner of the award decision and of the reasons why their tenders are not taken into account.
Procurement procedures may only be cancelled under certain conditions, e.g. where the bid prices are excessive or the tenders do not meet the requirements of the invitation to tender.
Different rules
In the Czech Republic, the 10-and 15 - day obligation to provide information and to wait for bids also applies to construction services not to be awarded throughout Europe.
In Germany,these requirements only apply to the area of EU-wide procurement.
In the case of other proceedings in Germany, tenderers can only be informed of the award decision after the award of the contract has been awarded.
In the Czech Republic, a procurement procedure must be cancelled if only one tender has been received or only one tender could be assessed.
In Germany, the contract must also be awarded in the case of only a single tender, provided that it meets the conditions of the invitation to tender and is economic.
