Documentation, reporting and reporting requirements
The award procedures shall be documented in a comprehensible manner during their individual stages in view of the relevant findings as well as the reasons for the individual decisions.
For EU-wide procedures, the contracts awarded must be made public.
Order data is also collected in EU statistics.
Requirements of EU law and the Prevention of corruption documentation of procurement procedures is a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement.
A carefully and timely documentation allows for the traceability of procurement decisions.
In particular, it also provides effective legal protection for tenderers in the case of contracts awarded above the EU thresholds.
Proper documentation is also an essential part of preventing corruption, as the compulsion to substantiate procurement decisions in detail, considerably restricts the scope for manipulation.
The contract notice for an EU-wide procurement procedure must be sent to the office for official publications of the EU within 48 days.
