Summary evaluation and recommendations
The parallel audits of the NKÚ and the BRH have focused on two main issues, which are in the Czech Republic and in Germany, essential for the award of construction contracts by Contracting authorities: the application of The EU procurement rules and the prevention of Corruption.
The requirements of EU law enable cross-border competition to create a European internal market.
Anti-corruption measures are not only used to prevent or at least reduce corruption. You should also avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.
The audit findings of the two sais on the application of public procurement rules in both countries, and the comparison of these rules, reveal similarities and differences that can be helpful for both countries in the development of their public procurement law and its application.
Application of EU procurement rules
The requirements of the EU for the award of construction services have been transposed into national law by both countries.
Thus, in the Czech Republic and Germany, there is an important common basis for the award of works and the consideration of the essential bids of competition, equal treatment of the undertakings involved and the transparency of the procurement procedures.
The building authorities of both countries have in some cases supported these bids very extensively by further administrative provisions.
The Czech Republic has largely transferred the requirements for EU-wide construction services to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.
However, the court of auditors ' investigations have shown that the building authorities have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.
The building administration in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to be able to remedy the identified objections when implementing the EU requirements.
In particular, the tests in the Czech Republic have shown dangers which affect the economic viability of the contracts.
Thus, incomplete specifications required additional services, which were often awarded in breach of legislation. In addition, the cost investigations were usually insufficiently prepared. Also, the number of potential tenderers was reduced by excessive skill requirements and competition was restricted, in particular in the case of transport structures.
The prevention of corruption
The investigations did not aim to detect corruption cases,
also because the sais do not have the appropriate tools to do so.
However, the sais can assess the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and Manipulation in the awarding of works and how these provisions are applied.
Both countries have set different priorities in preventing corruption.
In particular, the German regulations provide for largely unrestricted competition and transparency and controls as central elements of the Prevention of corruption.
The Czech regulations aim above all at greater transparency of procedures.
BRH
In Germany, general principles of corruption prevention apply, which the entire federal administration has to apply.
These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of works and are geared to their specific requirements.
In some cases, the relevant rules specify the manner in which anti-corruption bids are to be taken into account during the award procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.
In particular, the BRH considers that the overriding principle of the open procedure or the public procurement procedure is an appropriate Instrument to significantly reduce the risk of corruption in the award of works. Restrictions on competition, on the other hand, increase the risk of manipulation.
Risk analyses and adequate controls (especially the multi-eye principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures and various organisational measures are also effective measures to prevent corruption and Manipulation.
The BRH therefore sees no fundamental need for changes to the corresponding specifications of the administrations in the awarding of construction services.
The rules for preventing corruption are largely taken into account in practice.
The shortcomings identified in some areas have shown shortcomings in the implementation of certain requirements.
Building administrations should further train their staff on the guidelines for preventing corruption and raise their awareness of this issue even more.
A substantial part of the complaints related to tasks delegated by the building administration to freelancers.
Without controls and adequate safeguards, however, the risk of misuse increases when tasks are delegated.
Therefore, tasks at risk of manipulation and corruption should only be assigned to third parties if the administration can ensure a sufficient level of protection against inadmissible interventions.
NKÚ
The Czech Republic adopted at government level a strategy against corruption in which public procurement is the most important component.
The Procurement Act and its implementing rules have been substantially amended.
The Nkú audits took place during the implementation of this strategy.
The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions should be effective improvement measures, as contracting entities must justify the efficiency of the award of contracts, the calculation of expected prices, the adequacy of qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the type of evaluation, and duly document and publish all these aspects.
Make recommendations
The NKÚ the BRH to assess the implementation of the EU requirements, in principle, positive.
The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that EU bids of competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of works within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting cross-border competition.
In view of the enormous potential for material and immaterial damage caused by Manipulation and corruption in the award of construction services, both courts of auditors see the construction authorities in their countries as required to continue and, if necessary, to improve their measures against corruption and Manipulation.
In particular, the Organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously examined for vulnerabilities and risks in order to identify the need for action and to initiate appropriate countermeasures.
The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the proportion of open procedures should be increased in the Czech Republic, as open procedures can provide a wider scope for competition and significantly reduce the risk of corruption.
A greater division of works into lots may also have a beneficial effect on supply prices, provided that this results in greater competition with a higher number of tenderers.
Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for efficient contracting authorities ' procurement activities.
In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the specialised building authorities. In the Czech Republic, on the other hand, these tasks – with the exception of transport projects – are carried out by the departments themselves or by contractors appointed by them.
The sais of both countries have the aim, even after the completion of their joint project, to develop the relevant findings for them and, if necessary, to bring them to the parliament and government of their country.
Both sais are also convinced that the principles of Public Procurement Law as set out in this report and its implementation are also of interest at the international level of the International Organisation of supreme audit institutions (INTOSAI). Because the principles and findings are of General importance to corruption, countering effectively and to ensure economic procurement of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.
